e shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Kaber","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Muslim: variant of   Kabir  .","German (<b>Käber</b>): from an old vernacular form of an ancient Germanic personal name composed of the elements <i>geb</i> ‘gift’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’."],"variants":[{"name":"Keber","meanings":["German: probably a variant of <b>Käber</b> (see   Kaber  ).","Slovenian: nickname from <i>keber</i> ‘beetle, chafer’, a colloquial loanword from German (see   Kafer  )."]},{"name":"Kabir","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Humayun, Mohammed, Mohammad, Syed, Alamgir, Ahmed, Khairul, Mohamed, Mohmmad, Muhammed, Abdul, Abu.","Muslim: from a personal name based on Arabic <i>kabīr</i> ‘great, magnificent’. <i>Al-Kabīr</i> ‘the Great’ is an attribute of Allah. See also   Akbar  , compare   Kaber  ."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Hugh de Kaber was born about 1140, in France. She had at least 1 son with Hugh De KABER."},"et":{"about 1140–":"umbes 1140–Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","about 1140":"umbes 1140","1100":"1100","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","France":"Prantsusmaa","Fulthorpe, Darlington, Durham, England":"Darlington, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1140–":"noin 1140–Kuollut","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1140–Female":"1140–Kuollut","about 1140":"noin 1140","1100":"1100","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","France":"Ranska","Fulthorpe, Darlington, Durham, England":"Darlington, Durham, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1140–":"environ 1140–Décédée","1100–Male":"1100–Décédé","1170–Male":"1170–Décédé","1140–Female":"1140–Décédée","about 1140":"environ 1140","1100":"1100","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","France":"France","Fulthorpe, Darlington, Durham, England":"Darlington, Durham, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs Hugh de Kaber est née environ 1140, à France. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Hugh De KABER."},"de":{"about 1140–":"um 1140–Verstorben","1100–Male":"1100–Verstorben","1170–Male":"1170–Verstorben","1140–Female":"1140–Verstorben","about 1140":"um 1140","1100":"1100","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","France":"Frankreich","Fulthorpe, Darlington, Durham, England":"Darlington, Durham, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Mrs Hugh de Kaber wurde um 1140 in Frankreich geboren. Sie hatte mit Hugh De KABER mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"about 1140–":"about 1140–Desede","1100–Male":"1100–Desede","1170–Male":"1170–Desede","1140–Female":"1140–Desede","about 1140":"about 1140","1100":"1100","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","France":"France","Fulthorpe, Darlington, Durham, England":"Darlington, Durham, Angletè, United Kingdom"},"hu":{"abou